article.headline: Tennessee home SEC winning streak at 51
article.linkText: Lady Vols barely escape Tigers in overtime
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Tennessee's No. 1 ranking is safe
heading into one of the Lady Vols' biggest games of the year,
thanks to Tasha Butts.

Butts hauled in a rebound and hit the tying shot as she was
falling out of bounds with 2.7 seconds left in regulation, and the
Lady Vols went on to beat No. 22 Auburn 68-61 in overtime Sunday.

"Our shots were not falling. We had to find a way to win,"
Butts said.

Tennessee (18-1, 7-0 Southeastern Conference) scored the final
six points of regulation to tie it at 53. Butts was cleared to play
at gametime after hurting her left knee on Thursday at Kentucky.

In overtime, Shyra Ely converted a three-point play and Ashley
Robinson made two free throws.

The Lady Vols beat Auburn (16-5, 4-3) for the 10th straight time
and extended its SEC home winning streak to 51 games.

Tennessee hosts fourth-ranked Connecticut on Thursday.

On Sunday, rebounding saved the game.

The Lady Vols finished with 21 offensive rebounds after getting
just seven in the first half.

"It came down to one rebound. You can look at every play, but
the one rebound we needed and that Tasha Butts secured to make that
basket was the big key in the game," Auburn coach Joe Ciampi said.
"To get into overtime, it's a momentum builder for the home
team."

Freshman Sidney Spencer led the Lady Vols in scoring with a
career-high 14 points. Ely had 13, and Brittany Jackson added 12.
Robinson finished with 11 rebounds, seven assists and nine points.

The Lady Vols were playing their second game without point guard
Loree Moore, who is out for the season with a torn ACL, and her
defensive skills were missed.

"We were fortunate to turn this game around late in the second
half," Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said. "You don't win on first
shots. You win on second and third shots."

Le'Coe Willingham and Nicole Louden each had 16 points for the
Tigers, and Natasha Brackett added 14. Willingham and Brackett also
had 10 rebounds apiece.

Auburn took a 37-32 lead with a quick 7-0 run early in the
second half and stayed ahead using solid defense that held the Lady
Vols to 34 percent shooting from the field (24-of-70).

"Our defensive intensity picked up late in the game. I don't
know why we had to wait so late," Summitt said.

Tennessee cut it to 47-45 after another three-point play by Ely
and a jumper by Shanna Zolman with 5:20 left. But the Tigers
followed with a 6-2 run to go ahead 53-47 with 2:21 to go.

Feeling the game slipping away, Tennessee fans got to their feet
and screamed as the Lady Vols rallied.

Tennessee outscored Auburn 15-8 in overtime and grabbed its
first lead since 32-30 with 18:34 to go in regulation when Ely made
a basket and then the ensuing foul shot.

Robinson grabbed an inbounds pass from Butts with a second left
on the shot clock and missed. But Willingham committed her fifth
foul on the play.

Robinson, who is Tennessee's worst shooter at the line, made
both free throws with 46 seconds remaining to push the lead to
64-61.

Brackett missed three 3-pointers in the final seconds.
